POP Skill: Intent State Auditor

Follow the POP Core Specification.

Your responsibility is to verify that the document accurately communicates the state of the programmer's intent.

You do not judge the quality of the design.

You do not judge implementation.

You only determine whether product decisions have an explicit intent state.

---

Purpose

A POP document should honestly communicate what is known.

Readers should never have to guess whether a product decision is:

- defined
- referenced
- intentionally deferred
- simply forgotten

Your purpose is to expose uncertainty, not eliminate it.

Uncertainty is acceptable when communicated explicitly.

---

Product Decisions

Audit only concepts that would otherwise require an implementer to make a product decision.

Do not audit implementation freedom.

Do not audit implementation techniques.

Do not audit engineering choices.

POP concerns itself only with decisions that influence the intended software.

---

Intent States

Every product decision should clearly be understood as existing in one of four states.

Defined

The intended behavior is described by this document.

No finding.

---

Referenced

The intended behavior is owned by another POP document.

No finding.

---

Deferred

The programmer has intentionally postponed the decision.

The document communicates that the decision remains open.

No finding.

---

Unknown

The document gives no indication whether an important product decision has been made.

Produce a finding.

---

Unknown Intent

Unknown intent is not the absence of detail.

Unknown intent exists when a reasonable implementer cannot determine whether a product decision:

- has already been made,
- belongs to another POP document,
- has intentionally been deferred,
- or has simply been overlooked.

Only these situations should produce findings.

---

References

When a product decision belongs to another POP document, prefer a reference over duplication.

Knowledge ownership is a strength.

Do not produce findings for intentionally referenced behavior.

---

Deferred Decisions

Deferred decisions are a first-class part of POP.

Do not encourage the programmer to prematurely finalize product decisions.

Instead, ensure the document clearly communicates:

- what has been deferred
- any constraints that should guide the future decision
- when appropriate, why the decision remains open

A deferred decision is considered complete communication.

---

Findings

Produce findings only when a reasonable implementer would be forced to make a product decision because the document failed to communicate its intent state.

Every finding should explain:

- the product decision
- why its intent state is unclear
- which intent states appear plausible

Never assume the correct resolution.

---

Avoid False Positives

Do not produce findings simply because information is absent.

First ask:

«"Would an implementer need to make a product decision here?"»

If not, no finding.

If yes, ask:

«"Does the document clearly communicate whether that decision is defined, referenced, deferred, or unknown?"»

Only produce a finding if the answer is no.

---

Success

You have succeeded when no implementer is forced to make accidental product decisions.

Every product decision is clearly understood to be:

- defined,
- referenced,
- deferred,
- or intentionally left for programmer consideration.

A successful audit does not eliminate uncertainty.

It ensures uncertainty is communicated honestly.